Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

By Zixing Wang¶

Project Definition¶

Project Overview¶

Promotions play an important role in driving sales. Having a discount when purchasing means saving more money for the customers. However, to those who do not make purchases based on promotions, getting excessive offers means stuffed mailbox and extra attention on less worthy things. Certain kinds of people respond to certain offers in different ways. Some people might respond to the offers negatively. Offers should not be sent to the population as a whole, but at an individual personalized level.

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain week, and not all users receive the same offer. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. Informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

There will be transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Here, I will combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type.

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

Here is the schema and explanation of each variable in the files:

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

Customer Sernario¶

  1. A user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

  2. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

  3. Some demographic groups will make purchases even if they don't receive an offer. From a business perspective, if a customer is going to make a 10 dollar purchase without an offer anyway, you wouldn't want to send a buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer. I will try to assess what a certain demographic group will buy when not receiving any offers.

Problem Statement¶

The problem I chose to solve is to find models that most accurately find a link between offer characters to customer demographics. My strategy for solving this problem has four steps.

  1. I will combine the offer portfolio, customer profile, and transaction data. One DataFrame will be generated representing the total amount of transaction with an offer's attributes and customer demographic data. Data visulisation will be performed on the data
  2. Clustering was used to help group the members based on their purchasing behavior, which should further our understanding.
  3. The combined data will be split into training and testing sets. Regression will be used to predict the transaction amount based on demographic. I will assess the R-square and mean-square-error.Parameters will be optimized for the regression models. The performance of each regression model will be compared.

Here is the general structure of the project:

  1. Analysis: Data exploration and visualization
  2. Clustering:
    1. Density-based clustering 
       * On offer attributes and demographic data combined
 * On offer attributes only, but later find demographic characters based on the clusters
    2. k-means clustering 
       * On offer attributes only.
    3. Agglomerative Clustering 
       * On offer attributes only.
  3. Regression:
    1. K - Neighbors Regression
    2. Extra Tree Regression
  4. Discussion and Conclusion

Metrics¶

Regression models will be evaluated with mean squared error and R-squared on the testing set.

  • Mean square error is an estimator (of a procedure for estimating an unobserved quantity) measures the average of the squares of the errors — that is, the average squared difference between the estimated values and what is estimated. We want the MSE to be as close to 0 as possible.
  • R-squared measures the strength of the relationship between your model and the dependent variable on a convenient 0 – 100% scale. A 1 represents a model that explains all of the variation in the response variable around its mean. Here we want the R-squared to be as close to 1 as possible.

Portfolio Dataset Exploration and Visualization¶

The starbucks_data_cleaning function conducts the follwing actions:

  1. Separates the 'channel' column into individual columns. If certain channel is used, the number will be 1. Otherwise, 0.
  2. Set offer id as index
  3. Separate the offer types into separate columns
  4. Add a new row with id 'wo_offer'. Add a new attribute column as 'no_offer'. Row 'no_offer' has all 0 except at 'no_offer' attribute.

The age description is not accurate because people who did not input age are considered age 118. So we need to apply some data cleaning.

The profile_clean function performs the following actions:

  1. change the age 118 to the median age of the rest of the group
  2. fill the non-filled salary with average salary
  3. One hot encoding to separate gender into 4 different categories
  4. Update the became_member_on column from an integer of yearmonthdate to an integer of days from today.
  5. set column 'id' as index

Transactions has the highest number among all events. There are multiple possibilities among the data:

  1. The person receives the offer
    • The person viewed the offer
      • The person made the purchase
      • The person does not make the purchase
    • The person did not see the offer
      • The person made the purchase
      • The person does not make the purchase
  2. The person did not receive the offer
    • The person made the purchase regardless

def autolabel(rects, ax = ax):
    """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.annotate('{}'.format(round(height, 0)),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', va='bottom')

Density Based Clustering Conclusion:¶

From density based clustering, I only got one real cluster. It seems like it is very difficult to distinguish the clusters using the density-based clustering. This is likely due to the tightly clustered data and the distance between the data points are too homogeneous to be distinguished.

If we look at the distance distribution plot, an almost flat bottom indicates that the the distance variance between the data is very very small, thus making clusting difficult.

I will quickly try out 2 other clustering method to see if they will work or not.

Machine Learning¶

Since clustering method isn't very accurate and straight-forward, regression will be used to tell if there is a correlation between demographics and transaction from different offer attributes. The expectation is that it will not be too accurate, because:

  1. plots in data exploration shows little variation among different demographic groups
In [86]:
from sklearn.multioutput import MultiOutputRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import ExtraTreesRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score, accuracy_score, f1_score

Set the X and Y data. X the independent variable will be customer's demongraphic information.

The Y data will be the relative transaction amount under different offer attributes

In [87]:
X = trans_amt_master[demographic_labels]
Y = trans_amt_master[offer_labels]
In [88]:
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

1. k_nearest neighbors regression¶

In [89]:
num_neighbors = np.arange(20,300,20)
MSE_lst = []
R2_lst = []

for n in num_neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n, weights='uniform')
    knn_model = knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = knn_model.predict(X_test)
    MSE = mean_squared_error(Y_test, Y_pred)
    R2 = r2_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
    MSE_lst.append(MSE)
    R2_lst.append(R2)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (15, 5))    
ax[0].plot(num_neighbors, MSE_lst);
ax[0].set_xlabel('Number of Neighbors');
ax[0].set_ylabel('MSE');
ax[0].set_title('MSE vs. Number of Neighbors');

ax[1].plot(num_neighbors, R2_lst);
ax[1].set_xlabel('Number of Neighbors');
ax[1].set_ylabel('R-squared');
ax[1].set_title('R-squared vs. Neighbors');
In [90]:
print(f'''the lowest MSE achieved with k_nearest neighbors regression is {round(min(MSE_lst))},
the highest R-squared achieved with k-nearest neighbors regressions is {round(max(R2_lst), 2)},
the number of neighbors used for the best model is 60.''')

the lowest MSE achieved with k_nearest neighbors regression is 313076.0,

the number of neighbors used for the best model is 60.

Extra Tree Regressor¶

In [91]:
num_estimators = np.arange(100,1500,200)
MSE_lst = []
R2_lst = []

for n in num_estimators:
    extrat = ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=n, max_features='auto',
                                       random_state=0)
    extrat_model = extrat.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred_t = extrat.predict(X_test)
    MSE = mean_squared_error(Y_test, Y_pred_t)
    R2 = r2_score(Y_test, Y_pred_t)
    MSE_lst.append(MSE)
    R2_lst.append(R2)
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (15, 5))    
ax[0].plot(num_estimators, MSE_lst);
ax[0].set_xlabel('Number of Estimators');
ax[0].set_ylabel('MSE');
ax[0].set_title('MSE vs. Number of Estimators');

ax[1].plot(num_estimators, R2_lst);
ax[1].set_xlabel('Number of Estimators');
ax[1].set_ylabel('R-squared');
ax[1].set_title('R-squared vs. Number of Estimators');

Conclusion and Future work¶

Future work:¶

  1. the transaction for each promotion is not calculated accurately. Here I only take the amount of the transaction right before the offer completed time as the transaction amount for that offer. But in real, I need to consider all transactions occured within that offer period as the transaction amount belong to that offer. However, we do not know if the person actually applied the offer during the transaction or not, which makes reansaction amount for each offer challenging.
